courses.learning_outcomes:
At the end of the course of studies, students are expected to acquire the ability to
1. understand basic structural programming constructs in building a working software;
2. apply computer programming to solve engineering problems;
3. model a system on a computer to meet specifications and performance goals.

1. Be able to write, understand, compile and debug C++ programs;
2. Be able to write programs using the basic programming elements such as variables, data types, selection and looping control structures, functions, and arrays;
3. Be able to perform dynamic memory allocation and manage pointers;
4. Be able to implement and instantiate classes, and invoke methods;
5. Understand the basic concept of data encapsulation, polymorphism, and inheritance;

1. To be able to implement the following data structures as abstract data types in a high level programming language: stack, queue, hash table, list, binary search tree (including AVL tree, red black tree and splay tree), B-tree, trie, disjoint set, graph (including minimum spanning tree and shortest path);
2. To be able to use appropriate data structures in different applications;
3. To be able to implement abstract data types;
4. To be able to analyse the complexity of simple algorithms (such as searching and sorting).

At the end of the course of studies, students will have acquired the ability to

1. Understand the principles and technologies involved in building a web application;
2. Gain a better insight into emerging web technologies for building web applications;
3. Create interactive dynamic websites and web applications.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:
- Explain the basic principles of biomechanics;
- Apply the above principles to facilitate quantitative understanding of the normal functions of the musculoskeletal system for locomotion, postural control, and other daily activities;
- Apply the above principles to analyze the biomechanical consequences of the pathological conditions of the musculoskeletal system, its injury mechanisms, how the system can adapt itself to meet its functional demands, and how clinical orthopaedic interventions may facilitate the healing of its derangements.

Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to:
1. explain the meanings of signals and systems from engineering perspectives and with connection to real-world applications;
2. demonstrate how signals and systems can be represented by mathematical expressions;
3. explain the concepts of frequency and frequency spectrum;
4. describe and explain the types and properties of systems, with an emphasis on linear time-invariant systems;
5. use Laplace transform or z-transform to represent a linear system;
6. analyze and explain the behavior of a linear system;
7. explain the sampling theorem and its physical implications.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1. appreciate that concepts of signals and systems can be used in a wide variety of disciplines and applications;
2. recognize the power of working in transform domains; to take advantage of the complementary insights and tools that these
different perspectives provide;
3. recognize system properties such as causality, stability, linearity, and time invariance;
4. perform time-domain analysis of linear time-invariant (LTI) systems; in particular performing convolution in continuous and
discrete time;
5. analyze LTI systems and their properties through determination and examination of the impulse response;
6. use and compute Fourier series to analyze periodic signals and the response of LTI systems to such signals;
7. use Fourier transform methods to analyze general signals, including both aperiodic and periodic signals;
8. use frequency domain methods to analyze the effects of LTI filters on signals;
9. understand the sampling theorem and, more generally, the impact in both the time and frequency domains of sampling;
10. analyze signals and LTI systems using Laplace transforms; and
11. analyze signals and LTI systems using z-transforms.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to understand the basic principles of engineering mechanics including both statics and dynamics;
(2) be able to interpret, simplify, and model given engineering problem situations;
(3) be able to work as individuals to conduct his/her engineering analysis through written descriptions or by oral presentation in a professional manner;
(4) be able to apply the fundamentals of mechanics to the preliminary design and evaluation of mechanical systems;
(5) be able to understand the mathematical models used for analysis and design;
(6) be able to apply the basic principles of particle and rigid body kinematics and dynamic analysis;
(7) be able to use different methods of approaching dynamics problems, such as work and energy, and impulse and momentum.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) apply the laws of thermodynamics to simple systems;
(2) formulate various types of energy transfer between systems or a system and its surroundings mathematically;
(3) solve simplified problems in thermodynamics by using appropriate tables and graphs;
(4) describe the fundamental principles behind various types of heat engines, refrigerators and heat pumps;
(5) model various types of heat engines, refrigerators and heat pumps and discuss their efficiencies.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the fundamentals of psychrometrics, air-handling process;
(2) understand the working principles of the single-zone systems, CAV and VAV systems;
(3) understand the working principles of the hydronic system and central plant;
(4) understand the fundamentals of thermal comfort, ventilation and indoor air quality.

This course contributes to the following EEEN Programme Learning Outcomes:
(1) E1: Acquired basic knowledge related to energy and environmental engineering, including physics, mathematics, thermodynamics, energy technologies, power systems, environmental economics, building control and assessment, air pollution, etc. (K,S);
(2) E3: Developed the ability to design and build engineering components, structures, processes or systems to meet targeted needs in specific energy and environmental applications (K,S);
(3) E4: Acquired the ability to function as a member of an interdisciplinary team (S,V);
(4) E5: Acquired the ability to identify, formulate and solve real-life engineering problems and tradeoffs related to energy system and optimization, environmental monitoring and control, and green building technologies (K,S);
(5) E7: Developed proficiency in technical communication (both oral and written) (S);
(6) E11: Acquired the ability to use the techniques, skills and tools to practice in the energy and environmental engineering discipline and be aware of entrepreneur opportunities (K,S);
(7) E12: Acquired the ability to use the computer/IT tools relevant to the discipline along with an understanding of their processes and limitations (K,S,V);
(8) E13: Established a good understanding and vision of the energy and environmental industries in terms of technologies, tradeoffs and impacts (K).

K = Knowledge outcomes; S = Skills outcomes; V = Values and attitude outcomes.

Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to:
1. apply mathematical methods to explain and analyze electromagnetic field and wave propagation problems;
2. explain the working principles of common microwave and optical transmission lines and devices;
3. design a simple antenna and a matching network, and conduct relevant measurement using a vector network analyzer;
4. describe key practical issues and technical challenges in radio and optical communication systems.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1. demonstrate basic knowledge and understanding of digital communications;
2. follow methods and algorithms commonly used in digital communications;
3. apply principles and analytical techniques to investigate simple digital communication systems;
4. compare different algorithms and analytical techniques in digital communications, and the strengths and weaknesses of
different digital communication systems; and
5. design and optimize simple digital communication systems.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1. understand the basic principles in the Markov Chain and Martingale;

2. acquire intuitive concepts underlying the basic theory of stochastic processes;

3. associate some key concepts with short mnemonic expressions so that the acquired knowledge can last a long time;

4. appreciate the role and function of probability models in problem analysis;

5. improve their general ability of logical reasoning and clear presentation; and

6. acquire the capability of using simulations as a principled/reinforced method in evaluating systems/situations with randomness.

Upon completion of this course, students will:
1. gain conceptual knowledge in the social and human dimensions of social media;
2. gain conceptual as well as practical knowledge in social media modeling and analysis;
3. be able to integrate theories and concepts in human information interaction into the analytics and visualization of large scale social media.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) describe present global energy issues, including the pros and cons of different kinds of energy technologies, and challenges in meeting energy demand and energy conservation;
(2) explain the short- and long-term impacts of these energy issues on human activities and behaviours;
(3) perform basic quantitative analyses to evaluate and study the relationship between energy consumption, environment, and economic growth;
(4) model human decision making in simple scenarios using game theory;
(5) analyze the benefits, impacts and challenges brought by new developments in different sectors, such as electricity generation, transportation and heating and cooling.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) describe the basic structures and key properties of engineering materials;
(2) select engineering materials for a given application purpose by evaluating their structure-property-performance relationship;
(3) understand the functions of various analytical and material characterization tools in characterizing the properties of various engineering materials;
(4) utilize various physical, chemical, and material techniques in the modeling, and performance evaluation of engineering materials for given engineering applications;
(5) conduct various characterization instruments for analysis and design;
(6) quantitatively evaluate the suitableness and the properties of various energy storage technologies for engineering applications;
(7) design engineering materials upon given an application with desired performance and application specifications.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the core technologies of manufacturing, their features, benefits and limitations;
(2) be skilled at communicating with appropriate media, including written reports and oral presentations on the core technologies of manufacturing;
(3) understand the important aspects of manufacturing by applying IT technologies;
(4) understand the influences of technological, environmental, social and cultural considerations on design and manufacturing decisions.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to to qualitatively and quantitatively ascertain the advantages and disadvantages of closed loop system;
(2) be able to utilize various mathematical techniques in the modeling, stability analysis and performance evaluation of close loop system;
(3) understand the needed trade-off in a design process;
(4) understand the characteristics and analytical tools in different control design method;
(5) be able to use the computation tools Matlab for analysis and design;
(6) design a controller upon given a system and desired performance specifications;
(7) be able to conduct assigned system and control experiments to verify predicted phenomenon.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) solve the forward and inverse kinematics problems in robot manipulators;
(2) generate and analyse the Jacobian matrix, singularities and workspace in robot manipulators;
(3) perform trajectory generation and motion planning in robot manipulators;
(4) formulate the dynamics of robot manipulators;
(5) understand the use and the significance of sensors and actuators in robotics;
(6) apply fundamental knowledge of kinematics and motion planning on real robot hardware;
(7) appreciate the significance of robotics to the society.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the control strategies of CAV and VAV systems;
(2) understand the control strategies of chilled/cooling water system and central plant;
(3) understand the fundamentals of building automation systems;
(4) understand the fundamentals of thermal insulation, heating/cooling load calculations, ventilation and infiltration.

