courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1. understand the basic transmission characteristics of optical fiber;

2. understand the basic structure and properties of optical sources and detectors in optical transmission systems;

3. understand the basic structure and properties of common optical components in optical systems and networks;

4. design simple optical transmission systems and evaluate its system performance; and

5. appreciate different kind of optical systems and networks.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1 demonstrate Knowledge and understanding of essential concepts, methods, and technologies of crytography;

2. understand various cryptographic primitives, their security properties, and applicaitons.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:
1. Understand the cryptographic concepts of blockchain as a distributed ledger;
2. Describe the issues of trust, anonymity and consensus mechanisms;
3. Describe and understand the differences between different types of blockchain structures;
4. Understand the applications of blockchain in various applications, as well as their challenges.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the principles and prospective of kinetic energy harvesting technologies;
(2) grasp the principles of different kinds of energy harvesters, their role in kinetic energy harvesting systems, their constraints, and application preferences;
(3) develop models for analysis and optimization of kinetic energy harvesting systems;
(4) experience the application oriented design, fabrication, and testing of kinetic energy harvesting devices;
(5) explore applications on kinetic energy harvesting for making good use of the energy.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the importance of utilizing solar energy and the major advantages and limitations of photovoltaic technologies;
(2) understand the working principles of photovoltaics (PVs) and the fundamental limitation of their performance;
(3) recognize the main advantages and drawbacks of different photovoltaic technologies, including crystalline PVs, thin-film PVs, and organic and nanostructure based PVs;
(4) understand how to calculate the cost of a solar panel system and be able to compare the cost aspects of different PV technologies;
(5) perform the basic steps to design a complete solar system for a particular application and to perform quantitative analysis for PV materials and PV cell performance;
(6) understand the relation between government policy and solar technology market.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) obtain the foundation knowledge of elementary quantum physics and its applications in nuclear power plant design;
(2) know design principles of different types of nuclear power plants and apply engineering knowledge to perform basic quantitative analysis;
(3) obtain the general knowledge of nuclear power plant management, waste processing, and risk management, and related environmental issues.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the design and implementation of specific computer-integrated manufacturing technologies addressed during the course;
(2) understand the strategic aspects and processes of new product design and manufacturing by applying computer integrated manufacturing technology;
(3) be able to skill at communicating with appropriate media, including mathematical graphical representations; (engineering drawings), written reports and oral presentations;
(4) be able to introduce the influences of technological, environmental, social and cultural considerations on design and manufacturing decisions;
(5) be able to identify the target markets and customers, strategic product features and benefits of the new design and manufacturing methods.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to apply knowledge of engineering mathematics and science to finite element modelling and analysis;
(2) be able to design components using the finite element method to meet target need within constraint in the aspects of safety, manufacturability, sustainability, etc.;
(3) be able to formulate and solve mathematic equations for engineering problems using the finite element method;
(4) be able to use the computer / IT tools relevant to the finite element method along with understanding of their procedure and limitation.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) identify and explain the underlying heat transfer mechanisms of physical phenomena correctly;
(2) apply appropriate models to describe heat transfer problems mathematically;
(3) solve the formulated heat transfer problems to find the rate of heat transfer and temperature at specified locations.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) analyze the principles of actuators, sensors, as well as electronics and hardware components on the integration and application of mechatronic systems;
(2) design, build, program and troubleshoot mechatronic systems;
(3) competent to work as individuals and as members of a small team to communicate the results in a professional manner.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to derive a state-space model for a given physical system;
(2) be able to perform stability analysis and computer simulation of time responses of the model;
(3) be able to perform various feedback controller design methods such as pole placement, observer design, feedforward design, internal model design, LQR method for fulfilling different design specifications;
(4) be able to analyze and design a discrete-time control system in both frequency domain and time domain.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to formulate various engineering design problems into optimization problems;
(2) be able to solve various optimization problems including both linear and nonlinear programming, both analytic and numeric methods, and both constrained and unconstrained problems;
(3) be able to apply various optimization approaches to design problems encompassing mechanical engineering, electrical engineering, and manufacturing engineering.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to use the principles of thermochemistry, fluid dynamics, and chemical kinetics to understand the basic combustion process;
(2) be able to calculate flame temperature for an idealized fuel-air mixture;
(3) be able to understand qualitatively how non-ideal factors affect flame temperature;
(4) be able to understand the difference between the basic types of internal combustion engines;
(5) be able to analyze an ideal engine cycle using thermodynamic diagrams and analyze the system performance of ideal Otto, Diesel and Brayton thermodynamic cycles;
(6) be able to analyze how CO, NO, unburned hydrocarbons and soot emissions are formed in engines and solutions to minimize them.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to explain the role of energy and storage technology and quantitatively explain the fundamental working principles of major energy storage devices and systems;
(2) be able to utilize various physical, chemical, electrochemical, and mathematical techniques in the modeling, and performance evaluation of energy storage devices and systems;
(3) understand the functions of various analytical tools in characterizing the performance of various energy storage devices and systems;
(4) be able to use the impedance characterization tools and instruments for analysis and design;
(5) be able to quantitatively evaluate the suitableness and the performance of various energy storage technologies for given an energy application purpose;
(6) be able to fabricate lab scale energy storage devices and conduct performance characterization and analysis;
(7) design an energy storage system upon given an application with desired performance specifications;
(8) be able to integrate experimental results and literature review into effective technical writing and oral presentation for communication.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the fundamental and principle of designing, controlling and operating power systems with energy generation, distribution, and consumption;
(2) understand the power system control and operation techniques;
(3) understand challenges and techniques of designing and operating smart grid with renewable energy integration;
(4) be able to explain the basic concepts and working principles of power system;
(5) be able to analyze and formulate basic power system, as well as selected systems with renewable energy and energy storage integration.

Upon completion of this course, students would be able to:
- Acquire sound understanding of the latest technologies that are impacting the business world every day;
- Understand the challenges faced by the business world in coping with changing business environments, higher customer sophistication and technological innovation;
- Gain practical experience in planning and delivering a group project on latest technologies;
- Acquire and practice planning, communication, facilitation, team work and logical thinking skills through active class participation, individual research paper and hands-on work on the final group project and presentation.

At the completion of the course, the students should have the ability to:
1. master the basic knowledge of probability and statistical modeling in financial engineering;
2. appreciate the inherent features of financial markets and understand how to use time series models (including GARCH model) to model and to predict the market movement;
3. use statistical analysis to analyze the market data, to support investment decision and to determine option price;
4. use software tools to implement statistical applications for financial analysis.
